cards.body:
Data type tells C: what kind of value goes in this box, and how much memory to use.

int    → whole numbers      → 4 bytes  → Range: -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647
       Example: int count = 5;

float  → decimal numbers    → 4 bytes  → 6-7 decimal digits precision
       Example: float pi = 3.14;

double → bigger decimals    → 8 bytes  → 15-16 decimal digits precision
       Example: double precise = 3.14159265;

char   → single character   → 1 byte   → stores one letter/symbol
       Example: char letter = 'A';

void   → no value / nothing → 0 bytes
       Used for functions that return nothing

if-else lets your program make decisions based on conditions.

Syntax:
if (condition) {
    // runs if condition is TRUE (non-zero)
} else if (another condition) {
    // runs if first was false but this is true
} else {
    // runs if ALL above conditions are false
}

A condition is anything that evaluates to 0 (false) or non-zero (true).

cards.example:
int marks = 75;

if (marks >= 90) {
    printf("Grade A");
} else if (marks >= 75) {
    printf("Grade B");  // ← this runs
} else if (marks >= 60) {
    printf("Grade C");
} else {
    printf("Fail");
}

cards.body:
Use for loop when you know exactly how many times to repeat.

Syntax:
for (start; condition; update) {
    // code to repeat
}

  start     → runs ONCE before loop begins
  condition → checked BEFORE each iteration (if false, loop stops)
  update    → runs AFTER each iteration

Example: Print 1 to 5
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    printf("%d ", i);
}

What happens:
  i=1: 1<=5 true → print 1 → i becomes 2
  i=2: 2<=5 true → print 2 → i becomes 3
  ... 
  i=6: 6<=5 false → STOP

cards.example:
Sum of numbers 1 to 10:
int sum = 0;
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    sum += i;
}
printf("%d", sum); // prints 55

cards.body:
WHILE LOOP — checks condition BEFORE running:
while (condition) {
    // repeats as long as condition is true
}

int i = 1;
while (i <= 5) {
    printf("%d ", i);
    i++;
}
// prints: 1 2 3 4 5

DO-WHILE LOOP — runs ONCE first, then checks:
do {
    // runs at least once
} while (condition);

int i = 10;
do {
    printf("%d", i); // prints 10 even though condition is false
} while (i < 5);     // condition false, loop stops after 1 run

cards.example:
Key difference:
while → may run 0 times (if condition is false from start)
do-while → runs at LEAST 1 time no matter what

cards.body:
BREAK — immediately exits the loop:
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    if (i == 5) break;  // stops when i is 5
    printf("%d ", i);
}
// Output: 1 2 3 4

CONTINUE — skips current iteration, goes to next:
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i == 3) continue;  // skips when i is 3
    printf("%d ", i);
}
// Output: 1 2 4 5  (3 is skipped)

SWITCH — cleaner alternative to many if-else:
switch (day) {
    case 1: printf("Monday"); break;
    case 2: printf("Tuesday"); break;
    default: printf("Other day");
}

SYNTAX:
return_type function_name(parameters) {
    // code
    return value;
}

Example — function to add two numbers:
int add(int a, int b) {
    int result = a + b;
    return result;
}

int main() {
    int answer = add(3, 5);  // calling the function
    printf("%d", answer);    // prints 8
    return 0;
}

Breaking it down:
  int        → return type (this function gives back a whole number)
  add        → function name (you choose this)
  int a, int b → parameters (inputs it receives)
  return result → sends the answer back to whoever called it

