cards.body:
When you pass a variable to a function, C has 2 ways:

CALL BY VALUE (default in C):
→ A COPY of the value is sent to the function
→ Original variable is NOT changed

void doubleIt(int x) {
    x = x * 2;  // changes the copy, not original
}
int n = 5;
doubleIt(n);
printf("%d", n);  // still prints 5!

CALL BY REFERENCE (using pointers):
→ The ADDRESS of the variable is sent
→ Function changes the ORIGINAL variable

void doubleIt(int *x) {
    *x = *x * 2;  // changes the original
}
int n = 5;
doubleIt(&n);     // & sends the address
printf("%d", n);  // now prints 10!

